=========================================================
FUNCTION OVERLOADING IN C++ (INTERVIEW NOTES)
=========================================================

Definition:
Function Overloading allows multiple functions to have the same name
but different parameter lists in the same scope.

It is an example of:

Compile-Time Polymorphism
(Early Binding / Static Binding)

=========================================================
WHY DO WE NEED FUNCTION OVERLOADING?
=========================================================

Without Overloading:

addInt()
addDouble()
addFloat()

Different names for similar operations.

With Overloading:

add()

Same interface, different implementations.

Improves:
• Readability
• Reusability
• Maintainability

=========================================================
BASIC SYNTAX
=========================================================

return_type function_name(parameter_list);

Functions can differ by:

1. Number of parameters
2. Type of parameters
3. Order of parameters

=========================================================
EXAMPLE 1: DIFFERENT NUMBER OF PARAMETERS
=========================================================

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Calculator
{
public:
    int add(int a, int b)
    {
        return a + b;
    }

    int add(int a, int b, int c)
    {
        return a + b + c;
    }
};

Output:

add(1,2);
add(1,2,3);

=========================================================
EXAMPLE 2: DIFFERENT PARAMETER TYPES
=========================================================

class Calculator
{
public:
    int add(int a, int b)
    {
        return a + b;
    }

    double add(double a, double b)
    {
        return a + b;
    }
};

Output:

add(10,20);
add(10.5,20.5);

=========================================================
EXAMPLE 3: DIFFERENT ORDER OF PARAMETERS
=========================================================

class Test
{
public:
    void fun(int x, double y)
    {
        cout << "Function 1";
    }

    void fun(double y, int x)
    {
        cout << "Function 2";
    }
};

=========================================================
HOW DOES COMPILER RESOLVE OVERLOADING?
=========================================================

Compiler performs:

Overload Resolution

Steps:

1. Exact Match
2. Promotion
3. Standard Conversion
4. User-defined Conversion

=========================================================
EXAMPLE
=========================================================

void fun(int)
{
    cout << "int";
}

void fun(double)
{
    cout << "double";
}

fun(10);

Output:

int

Exact match wins.

=========================================================
TYPE PROMOTION
=========================================================

void fun(int)
{
    cout << "int";
}

void fun(double)
{
    cout << "double";
}

char c = 'A';

fun(c);

Output:

int

Reason:
char → int promotion.

=========================================================
AMBIGUOUS OVERLOADING
=========================================================

void fun(long)
{
}

void fun(double)
{
}

fun(10);

Compilation Error:

Ambiguous call.

Reason:
Compiler cannot determine the best match.

=========================================================
FUNCTIONS CANNOT BE OVERLOADED BY
=========================================================

1. Return Type Alone
2. Parameter Names
3. Default Arguments (if ambiguity occurs)

=========================================================
NOT ALLOWED: RETURN TYPE ONLY
=========================================================

int fun()
{
    return 1;
}

double fun()
{
    return 1.0;
}

Compilation Error.

Reason:

Return type is NOT part of function signature.

=========================================================
NOT ALLOWED: PARAMETER NAMES ONLY
=========================================================

void fun(int x)
{
}

void fun(int y)
{
}

Compilation Error.

Reason:

Parameter names are ignored.

=========================================================
DEFAULT ARGUMENT AMBIGUITY
=========================================================

void fun(int x)
{
}

void fun(int x, int y = 0)
{
}

fun(10);

Compilation Error.

Reason:
Both functions match.

=========================================================
FUNCTION SIGNATURE
=========================================================

Includes:

• Function Name
• Number of Parameters
• Parameter Types
• Parameter Order

Does NOT Include:

• Return Type
• Parameter Names
• Default Values

=========================================================
OVERLOADING WITH CONST
=========================================================

Allowed:

void fun(int)
{
}

void fun(const int)
{
}

Not allowed.

Reason:
Top-level const is ignored.

---------------------------------------------------------

Allowed:

void fun(int*)
{
}

void fun(const int*)
{
}

Reason:
Pointer types are different.

=========================================================
FUNCTION OVERLOADING vs FUNCTION OVERRIDING
=========================================================

Feature              Overloading          Overriding
-----------------------------------------------------------
Polymorphism         Compile-Time         Runtime
Inheritance Needed   No                   Yes
Function Name        Same                 Same
Parameters           Different            Same
Virtual Needed       No                   Yes

